Midnight & my midnight thoughts just have me feeling a lot of things. 

Another January 29th… another reminder of how much life has changed over the last 4 years. 

Four years ago today, I launched A Blonde and Her Dog. I was filled with so much hope and so much joy to pour into this platform. Little did I know that three short days later— my Dad would unexpectedly pass away. 

Grief is still raw. It still comes in waves. I find peace in knowing it’s okay not to always be okay. I think social media can paint an unrealistic picture of what reality always looks like behind the scenes. 

The road to officially launching A Blonde and Her Dog has been far from easy. It took me until November 2019 to pick it up again. Four years later, I’ve worked with some of my dream brands and connected with some of the sweetest souls. Not a day goes by I’m not grateful for this community. Y’all have been here with me through some of my darkest days. 

I’ve worn this bracelet everyday since the day my Dad passed. It’s a simple reminder on even the hardest days— it will be okay.

Four years. 

I almost cannot believe I’m typing that out. Four whole years since A Blonde and Her Dog started 🩷 

When someone asks me how long I’ve been working as a content creator— I never quite know how to answer that question. 

The last few years, Novembers just feel…. different. To me, they’re almost a reminder through all life’s changes there’s always opportunity for a fresh start. 

I launched A Blonde and Her Dog late January 2019. I was about six months out of getting my bachelors degree and filled with a lot of hope, motivation, and dreams. Little did I know that three short days later, my dad would unexpectedly pass away. 

It took me until November 2019 to dive in and pour my heart into this platform… after I left the job that no longer served me. It’s both liberating and terrifying to do so. Self-employment is far from easy, but leaving a job completely toxic to my mental health was the best thing I could’ve ever done for me. 

The last four years have been filled with a lot of anxiety, grief, uncertainty, doubt, and fear. I’d be lying to say it hasn’t had it’s challenges, but I will always say this decision was one hundred percent worth it. 

This community has given me some of my closest friends. From followers who became friends, to others content creators who’ve inspired me and become my best friends, to brands who took a chance on me— y’all don’t know how much that means to me.

You believed in me when I didn’t believe in myself.. and I can’t thank you enough for that.

A lot has changed in four years— but my love for fashion, beauty, travel, lifestyle, and you all hasn’t.

The older I get, the more I realize everything we encounter is a lesson or a blessing. 

To everyone who has followed Tink & I’s journey— THANK YOU. Thank you for loving us, growing with us, and learning with us. 

Cheers to another year. I cannot wait to see what’s next 💫 

Xoxo, 
Kay & Tink
